  <!-- CONTENT SECTIONS -->
  <ContentSection
    id="signs-your-trees-canopy-is-too-dense"
    heading="Signs Your Tree's Canopy Is Too Dense"
    image={{ src: "/assets/crown-thinning-pruning-shears-branch-detail-denver.webp", alt: "Close-up of hand pruning shears cutting tree branch for crown thinning", title: "crown-thinning-pruning-shears-branch-detail-denver", align: "left" }}
  >
    <p>Most folks don't look up until something goes wrong. That's normal, but there are clues you can catch before a storm makes the decision for you.</p>
    <p>Stand under the tree at noon. See mostly shade, barely any light dappling through? That's a dense canopy. A healthy tree lets some sun filter down, enough to keep grass or shade plants alive underneath. If your lawn's gone patchy and thin right under the drip line, the canopy above it is probably choking out light it needs.</p>
    <p>Look for branches crossing and rubbing against each other. Over time that rubbing wears through bark, and that's an open door for disease and pests. We see this every single week on maples and honeylocust trees around older Denver neighborhoods like Park Hill, where the canopies have gone years without a trim.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Thick clusters of small twiggy growth bunched near the outer canopy</li>
      <li>Leaves only growing on the outside, with a bare, shaded interior</li>
      <li>Whole limbs that sway heavily in wind instead of flexing individually</li>
      <li>Visible dead or weak wood tangled inside the live growth</li>
      <li>A canopy that looks like a solid green ball instead of an open, layered shape</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Here's the one that gets people to finally call us. Denver's spring snowstorms drop wet, heavy snow while trees still have leaves or thick buds. A dense canopy catches that snow like a net, and the extra weight is exactly what snaps big limbs. Thinning the crown lets wind and snow pass through instead of piling up.</p>
  </ContentSection>

  <ContentSection
    id="crown-thinning-vs-crown-reduction-know-the-difference"
    heading="Crown Thinning vs. Crown Reduction: Know the Difference"
    alt={true}
    image={{ src: "/assets/crown-thinning-vs-reduction-result-denver.webp", alt: "Tree canopy after crown thinning shows more light reaching lawn in Denver", title: "crown-thinning-vs-reduction-result-denver", align: "right" }}
  >
    <p>Folks mix these up all the time, and we get it. Both jobs happen up in the canopy. Both involve a chainsaw and a lot of careful climbing. But they solve two completely different problems, and picking the wrong one can hurt the tree instead of helping it.</p>
    <p>Crown thinning removes select branches throughout the canopy to let light and air move through the tree. The tree keeps its natural shape and its overall size. Crown reduction, on the other hand, cuts back the outer branches to shrink the tree's overall height or spread, usually because it's grown too close to a roofline, a power line, or a neighbor's fence.</p>
    <p>Here's how we tell homeowners to think about it:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Thinning is about density. Too many branches crowded together, blocking wind and light.</li>
      <li>Reduction is about size. The tree's gotten too big for the space it's in.</li>
      <li>Thinning keeps the tree's natural form intact. Reduction changes its silhouette.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We see this mix-up a lot with older silver maples and honeylocusts around Denver, trees that have been growing for decades with no real pruning plan. The canopy gets so thick that wind can't pass through it, and that's when storm damage happens. A homeowner will ask for a "trim" thinking that means reduction, when what the tree needs is thinning to relieve that wind load.</p>
    <p>Most of the time, when someone calls us worried about a tree that "looks too full," thinning is the fix, not a full-scale reduction. Reduction cuts are bigger, they stress the tree more, and they should only happen when size is genuinely the issue. Getting this wrong means bigger wounds than necessary, and bigger wounds take longer to close up. An ISA-certified arborist can look at your tree and tell you in five minutes which one you need.</p>
  </ContentSection>

  <ContentSection
    id="when-crown-thinning-isnt-the-right-fix"
    heading="When Crown Thinning Isn't the Right Fix"
    image={{ src: "/assets/dense-canopy-signs-homeowner-view-denver.webp", alt: "Homeowner noticing overly dense tree canopy from kitchen window in Denver", title: "dense-canopy-signs-homeowner-view-denver", align: "left" }}
  >
    <p>Here's something not every tree company will tell you straight: crown thinning isn't always the answer. If your tree is leaning over the garage or has a split trunk, thinning the canopy won't fix that. That's a structural problem, and it usually calls for crown reduction or removal instead.</p>
    <p>We get calls all the time from folks who think their tree "just needs thinned out" when the real issue is deadwood. If most of what's bothering you is dead branches hanging over the driveway, that's deadwooding, not thinning. Different job, different result. Thinning opens up a healthy canopy so air and light move through it better. Deadwooding pulls out what's already dead or dying before it drops on someone's car.</p>
    <p>And if your tree's dropping large limbs during wind events, or you're seeing mushrooms at the base, thinning won't solve that either. That's a job for a tree risk assessment first. We've walked properties around Washington Park where big old silver maples look fine from the street but have serious internal decay from decades of poor pruning cuts. Thinning a tree like that just moves weight around, it doesn't fix the underlying problem.</p>
    <p>Young trees usually don't need thinning at all. A tree under five or six years old is still building its structure. Thinning it too early can slow it down.</p>
    <p>So ask yourself: is the canopy just dense, or is something wrong with the tree? Dense and healthy is a thinning job. Damaged, leaning, or diseased is something else entirely. A quick look usually tells us which one you're dealing with.</p>
  </ContentSection>

  <CtaBanner
    heading="Thinking about Crown Thinning in Denver? Let's talk."
    note="Call now for a free estimate. Arbor Care Tree Solutions is ready to help."
  />

  <ContentSection
    id="what-happens-during-a-professional-crown-thinning-visit"
    heading="What Happens During a Professional Crown Thinning Visit"
    alt={true}
    image={{ src: "/assets/crown-thinning-not-right-fix-inspection-denver.webp", alt: "Arborist inspecting tree trunk before recommending crown thinning in Denver", title: "crown-thinning-not-right-fix-inspection-denver", align: "right" }}
  >
    <p>Here's what happens when we show up for a crown thinning job. It's not just guys with chainsaws hacking away at random branches. There's a process, and skipping steps is how trees get hurt instead of helped.</p>
    <p>First, Thomas walks the property and looks at the whole tree, not just the branches you're worried about. He's got 30 years doing this, so he's checking crown density, branch attachment points, and whether the tree's even a good candidate for thinning in the first place. Some trees need it. Some don't. We'll tell you straight if yours falls into the second group.</p>
    <p>Once we're set to go, here's the general order of work:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="https://extension.colostate.edu/resource/pruning-mature-shade-trees/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Assess the crown and mark</a> which limbs come out, focusing on crossing branches and interior deadwood first.</li>
      <li>Set up climbing gear or rigging, depending on the tree's size and what's around it, like fences or a garage roof.</li>
      <li>Remove selected branches in small, controlled cuts, spreading the work evenly around the crown instead of stripping one side.</li>
      <li>Step back and check the canopy shape after every few cuts, not just at the end.</li>
      <li>Clean up every stick, chip, and leaf before we leave.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>That last step matters more than people think. We've pulled up to Denver homes near mature elm and ash canopies where a previous crew left brush piled against the fence line for weeks. That's not how we operate. Every job site gets left cleaner than we found it.</p>
    <p>And no, we don't rush this. Thinning done fast is thinning done wrong. We've seen the lopsided regrowth that follows a sloppy job more times than we'd like. A careful visit usually takes a few hours depending on the tree's size, but the time's worth it. You get a tree that still looks like a tree, just healthier and letting more light through.</p>
  </ContentSection>

  <ContentSection
    id="timing-crown-thinning-ahead-of-denvers-spring-snow-season"
    heading="Timing Crown Thinning Ahead of Denver's Spring Snow Season"
    image={{ src: "/assets/crown-thinning-before-snow-season-denver.webp", alt: "Tree crew thinning a canopy before Denver's snow season", title: "crown-thinning-before-snow-season-denver", align: "left" }}
  >
    <p>Denver gets some of its heaviest snow in March and April, not January. Front Range old-timers call it "Miracle March" for a reason. These late-season storms dump wet, heavy snow that clings to branches instead of the light powder you'd get in December. A crown packed with dense growth catches that snow like a net. Thin it out first, and the snow falls through instead of piling up on weak limbs.</p>
    <p>We schedule most crown thinning jobs in late winter, before the trees break dormancy and before those heavy spring storms roll in. This timing matters more here than in a lot of other places. Denver's swing from warm dry days to sudden snow dumps puts real stress on trees that are already carrying too much weight in their canopy. Thin branches out in February, and the tree heads into spring lighter and better able to shed snow load instead of snapping under it.</p>
    <p>Not every tree needs this on the same schedule, though. Fast growers like silver maple and cottonwood build up dense growth fast and benefit from thinning almost every year. Slower growers might only need it every few years. More often than not, when we get called out after a March snowstorm for storm damage cleanup, the tree that failed had a crown that hadn't been thinned in years.</p>
    <p>So what's the real window? Late winter, once the coldest stretch has passed but before buds start swelling. Wait too long into spring, and you're cutting into active growth, which stresses the tree more than it should. Wait too long overall, and you're rolling the dice on the next heavy snow.</p>
  </ContentSection>

